As recent actions by East Germany make German reunification more likely, many policy  wonks point out serious problems to be overcome.
A new structure or relationship  between NATO and the Warsaw Pact may be needed.
Theodore Sorenson, a top aide to  JFK, states that the U.S. couldn't afford a united Germany outside the Western Alliance  and the Soviets can't afford one inside the Western Alliance.
He hopes unification can be  forged within a reunited Europe.
William Hyland, a former aide to Henry Kissinger, and  former National Security Advisor, Zbigniew Brzezinski, expressed similar concerns  about conflicting European, U.S. and Soviet interests. 
